When using the distributive property for the first time, we add the product of $2p^2 - 1$ and $3p^2$ to the product of $2p^2 - 1$ and $4$:

\begin{align*}
(2p^2 - 1)(3p^2 + 4) &= (2p^2 - 1) \cdot (3p^2) + (2p^2 - 1) \cdot 4
\end{align*}We use the distributive property again and combine like terms:

\begin{align*}
(3p^2)(2p^2 - 1) + 4(2p^2 - 1) &= 6p^4 - 3p^2 + 8p^2 - 4\\
&= \boxed{6p^4 + 5p^2 - 4}
\end{align*}

There are $2^{10} = 1024$ ways to answer the questions on the true/false test. However, we can also compute the number of ways of answering the questions on the true/false test by using combinations; there are $\binom{10}{k}$ ways to answer $k$ of the questions on the test with a false, so we have: $$\binom{10}{0} + \binom{10}{1} + \cdots + \binom{10}{9} + \binom{10}{10} = 2^{10}.$$ The desired answer is \begin{align*}
&\binom{10}{3} + \binom{10}{4} + \cdots + \binom{10}{9} + \binom{10}{10} \\
=\text{ }&2^{10} - \binom{10}{0} - \binom{10}{1} - \binom{10}{2} = 1024 - 1 - 10 - 45 \\
=\text{ }&\boxed{968}.
\end{align*}

For $r = \sin 2 \theta,$
\begin{align*}
y &= r \sin \theta \\
&= \sin 2 \theta \sin \theta \\
&= 2 \sin^2 \theta \cos \theta \\
&= 2 (1 - \cos^2 \theta) \cos \theta.
\end{align*}Let $k = \cos \theta.$  Then $y = 2 (1 - k^2) k,$ and
\[y^2 = 4k^2 (1 - k^2)^2 = 4k^2 (1 - k^2)(1 - k^2).\]By AM-GM,
\[2k^2 (1 - k^2)(1 - k^2) \le \left( \frac{(2k^2) + (1 - k^2) + (1 - k^2)}{3} \right)^3 = \frac{8}{27},\]so
\[y^2 \le \frac{16}{27}.\]Hence,
\[|y| \le \sqrt{\frac{16}{27}} = \frac{4 \sqrt{3}}{9}.\]We get $y = \boxed{\frac{4 \sqrt{3}}{9}}$ when $k^2 = \cos^2 \theta = \frac{1}{3},$ so this is the maximum $y$-coordinate.

